{"title": "â€˜SNLâ€™ Writer Jimmy Fowlie Asks for Help Finding Missing Sister: â€˜Weâ€™re Worried She Isnâ€™t Safeâ€™", "link": "https://variety.com/2025/tv/news/snl-writer-jimmy-fowlie-missing-sister-1236616579/", "summary": "&#8220;Saturday Night Live&#8221; writer Jimmy Fowlie is asking for help finding his missing sister, Christina, who was last seen in Los Angeles. Fowlie shared his sister&#8217;s photo and phone number on his Instagram page and asked that if anybody has seen her to contact the police. According to her missing person report, Christina was last [&#8230;]", "content": "â€œSaturday Night Liveâ€ writer Jimmy Fowlie is asking for help finding his missing sister, Christina, who was last seen in Los Angeles.\n\nFowlie shared his sisterâ€™s photo and phone number on his Instagram page and asked that if anybody has seen her to contact the police. According to her missing person report, Christina was last contacted in late November.\n\nâ€œMy sister has been missing and we are worried that she isnâ€™t safe,â€ Fowlie wrote. â€œHer married name is Downer but she may go by Christina Fowlie. Please share this so that if anyone has seen her, they can give any information to the police. The phone number is 213-996-1800 and her case number is 25237639. She was last seen in LA. Thank you.â€\n\nSeveral of Fowlieâ€™s â€œSaturday Night Liveâ€ cast members, like Bowen Yang and Sarah Sherman, also shared his sisterâ€™s missing person report.\n\nPopular on Variety\n\nFowlie has been a writer on â€œSaturday Night Liveâ€ since 2022â€™s Season Season 48. He co-wrote the viral â€œDomingoâ€ sketch starring cast member Marcello Hernandez and host Ariana Grande last year. Before â€œSaturday Night Live,â€ he was a member of the Groundlings improv and sketch comedy group and has acted on shows like â€œThe Comeback,â€ â€œ2 Broke Girls,â€ â€œThe Other Two,â€ â€œSearch Party,â€ â€œEnglish Teacherâ€ and more. He also co-wrote and starred in the Off Broadway musical â€œSo Long Boulder City.â€\n\nLast weekend, â€œSaturday Night Liveâ€ aired its Christmas episode, hosted by Grande, and will return in January with host Finn Wolfhard and musical guest A$AP Rocky. It also marked Yangâ€™s final episode as a cast member.", "language": "en", "category": "entertainment", "source": "https://variety.com/feed/", "published": "Tue, 23 Dec 2025 15:39:37 +0000", "fetched_at": "2025-12-23T15:55:43.575217"}
{"title": "James Cameron on â€˜Avatar: Fire and Ash,â€™ Explaining Performance Capture in the Age of AI and Why He Isnâ€™t Ready to Talk About â€˜Avatar 4â€™", "link": "https://variety.com/2025/film/features/james-cameron-avatar-fire-and-ash-avatar-4-1236616244/", "summary": "â€œNous verrons,â€ says James Cameron when asked about a specific plot point in â€œAvatar 4.â€ (Thatâ€™s French for â€œwe shall see,â€ he tells Variety.) Itâ€™s the day after the â€œAvatar: Fire and Ashâ€ world premiere, and itâ€™s my turn to spend 10 minutes with the blockbuster filmmaker at the Four Seasons in Los Angeles, the [&#8230;]", "content": "â€œNous verrons,â€ says James Cameron when asked about a specific plot point in â€œAvatar 4.â€ (Thatâ€™s French for â€œwe shall see,â€ he tells Variety.)\n\nItâ€™s the day after the â€œAvatar: Fire and Ashâ€ world premiere, and itâ€™s my turn to spend 10 minutes with the blockbuster filmmaker at the Four Seasons in Los Angeles, the hallways and lobby of which have been transformed to resemble Pandora for the press junket. (Thus, one mightâ€™ve expected Cameron to slip a little Naâ€™vi into the interview, not French.)\n\nBut no matter what language he speaks, the filmmaker makes it known heâ€™s not keen to discuss the future of the franchise â€” at least, not until the box office returns have been counted.\n\nPopular on Variety\n\nâ€œWeâ€™re getting ahead of ourselves because, first of all, weâ€™ve got to make some money with this one,â€ Cameron says. â€œEvery time we go out, we have to prove this crazy business case yet again.\n\nâ€œThe world has changed. We all know the stats, where theatrical is. Itâ€™s been a bad year,â€ he goes on. â€œItâ€™s starting to perk up a little bit with a couple of recent releases: â€˜Wicked: For Goodâ€™ has done well, and â€˜Zootopia 2â€™ is doing well. So, weâ€™ll see.â€\n\nCameron is not being modest; heâ€™s a pragmatist. His â€œAvatarâ€ movies â€” about the adventures of Marine turned Naâ€™vi leader Jake Sully (Sam Worthington), Naâ€™vi warrior Neytiri (Zoe SaldaÃ±a) and their family â€” come with significant box office expectations. The original 2009 film and its 2022 sequel, â€œThe Way of Water,â€ stand as two of the highest-grossing movies in history, with $2.9 billion and $2.3 billion, respectively. â€œFire and Ashâ€ earned a strong $345 million globally in its opening weekend, but that figure is down from â€œThe Way of Waterâ€™sâ€ $435 million start.\n\nAs Varietyâ€™s Rebecca Rubin explains in her box office analysis, Disney spent a massive $350 million to produce the threequel and roughly $150 million to promote it, meaning the big-budget blockbuster needs to deliver in terms of ticket sales for Cameron to move forward with his planned fourth and fifth installments. (For the record, â€œAvatar 4â€ is slated for Dec. 2029 and a significant portion of the film has already been shot, while â€œAvatar 5â€ is expected to debut Dec. 2031.)\n\nIn the meantime, â€œAvatarâ€ super fans can also enjoy the making-of documentary, â€œFire and Water,â€ where Cameron reveals how his groundbreaking performance capture process really works. Here, Cameron reflects on how the Disney+ documentary is changing the conversation around performance capture, particularly in the age of generative artificial intelligence, and more about making the new movie, like introducing Oona Chaplinâ€™s villainous Varang and just how spicy her relationship with Quaritch (Stephen Lang) was intended to be.\n\nYouâ€™ve said that youâ€™re always a little nervous before these movies come out. Are you feeling a little better now?\n\nItâ€™s a good first step. People are responding well. I hadnâ€™t seen it with a big audience before [the premiere], because weâ€™ve done these small press screenings, and I donâ€™t really go to those. Thereâ€™s some laughs.\n\nDid any of those laughs surprise you?\n\nThe strength of a couple of them surprised me. And then thereâ€™s some applause too. There are moments that appear to be quite cathartic for the audience â€” some of the quieter, emotional stuff. For that, I just look at my wife, Suzy [Amis]; if sheâ€™s grabbing her tissues, then I know the sceneâ€™s working. Itâ€™s a little harder to read that in a big room.\n\nThe crowd applauded for Zoe SaldaÃ±aâ€™s performance as Neytiri. Youâ€™ve described her work on the â€œAvatarâ€ movies as â€œferocious,â€ and since we last spoke, sheâ€™s won an Oscar [for â€œEmilia PÃ©rezâ€]. Do you think pulling the curtain back on how performance capture technology works helps audiences appreciate her performance differently?\n\nThatâ€™s a really great way to put it. Thatâ€™s exactly what Iâ€™ve been doing. Iâ€™ve hidden the performance capture methodology because I thought, â€œI donâ€™t want to see people in a performance capture suit. I want them to think that the characters are real.â€ Right? But itâ€™s been such a disservice to these actors who are doing some of the best work in their careers. Iâ€™ve got Kate Winslet, Academy Award winner; Zoe SaldaÃ±a won an Academy Award last year; Sigourney Weaver, a highly respected actress, nominated multiple times. And I just think, â€œWhy am I hiding this under a bushel here? I should be celebrating it.â€\n\nJames Cameron (right) directing Zoe SaldaÃ±a and Sam Worthington on the set of â€œAvatar: Fire and Ash.â€ Mark Fellman\n\nWe just take all the cinematography â€” all the cameras and the lenses and the lighting and all that stuff â€” and we just shove it into the future. Itâ€™s like black box theater or a stage rehearsal. A lot of my cast have done theater, and they go, â€œOh, this is like, standing up a play.â€ Itâ€™s that quiet, intimate exploration. Everybody said, â€œWell, how can they possibly do that without all the sets and all the wardrobe?â€ Well, actors live in their imagination, right? And we give them the things they need. Sigourney said, â€œIâ€™d really like to have a shawl or something that I can kind of pull around myself and hide behind as this kind of sulky and misunderstood teenager.â€ Itâ€™s like, â€œSure, no problem.â€ Itâ€™s a wonderful process. And as a writer-director whoâ€™s created these characters, handing that baton to the actors, and then seeing what they do with it, thereâ€™s nothing better.\n\nI learned that Sigourney, who plays Kiri, the Sullysâ€™ adopted teenage daughter, actually narrates the next one.\n\nThat could be the case. Weâ€™re getting ahead of ourselves.\n\nOona Chaplinâ€™s character, Varang, who leads the Ash people, steals the show. But her relationship with Quaritch takes a sexier turn than some people might expect. Thereâ€™s a mutual seduction, but did you ever consider showing a Naâ€™vi sex scene?\n\nWe never really shot anything beyond what you see. Letâ€™s put it that way. We knew what we were going for was an undercurrent of sensuality, and itâ€™s a PG-13 movie as well.\n\nThe bigger question is, why did we spend 10 minutes â€” which is an eternity in screen time â€” not on our main characters, not on our protagonist characters? And the answer is very simple: Because it was cool. Thatâ€™s my ultimate modus operandi. If itâ€™s cool, weâ€™re gonna explore it. And Iâ€™m very proud of that scene where he goes to her, and they go inside the tent, and they tussle over the power. Itâ€™s a fun scene.\n\nOona Chaplin as Varang in â€œAvatar: Fire and Ash.â€ 20TH CENTURY STUDIOS\n\nMuch like Zoe, this film is a showcase for Oonaâ€™s talent. Many people know her from â€œGame of Thronesâ€ [Chaplin played Talisa Maegyr, Robb Starkâ€™s ill-fated wife], but this is her big screen breakout moment.\n\nI didnâ€™t know who Oona was when I cast her in 2016; I certainly hadnâ€™t seen [â€œGame of Thrones.â€]. But she had such a grasp of the character. Oona herself is just a very warm, beautiful, heartfelt person, almost the exact opposite [of Varang]. But isnâ€™t that fun to play the opposite and find you have the ability to play that. It can be a little scary.\n\nThatâ€™s that actor-director connection that you like to explore.\n\nIn an age of Gen AI chomping at the film industry, thatâ€™s another reason Iâ€™m pulling back the curtain to show that this is an actor-centric, artist-centric process, and we donâ€™t use those tools. Historically, we havenâ€™t used it at all.\n\nIâ€™m curious about what it can do thatâ€™s done ethically and constructively. I donâ€™t want to replace actors, even though people are stampeding to [saying,] â€œOh, I can make a film in my momâ€™s basement, and I donâ€™t need to pay any actors. How cool is that?â€\n\nIâ€™ve been mentoring some young filmmakers in New Zealand in a short film class, and I saw presentations for seven projects. All seven of them showed us their storyboards, their pre-viz, their music choices, their mood board, their character design. Not one of the presentations mentioned their cast. Afterwards, I said, â€œGuys, what the hell is going on here? You didnâ€™t lead with your actors. Do you have actors?â€ [They said,] â€œWell, yeah.â€ And I said, â€œWhy didnâ€™t you lead with that?â€ I said, â€œYou know what you all need to do when you get your films done? Go do some acting.â€ I think every director should do some acting. Thereâ€™s a lot of acting in directing.", "language": "en", "category": "entertainment", "source": "https://variety.com/feed/", "published": "Tue, 23 Dec 2025 16:30:00 +0000", "fetched_at": "2025-12-23T16:35:19.742509"}
{"title": "â€˜The Officeâ€™ Star Melora Hardin â€˜Burst Into Tearsâ€™ When Fired From â€˜Back to the Futureâ€™ Amid Michael J. Fox Recasting Drama: â€˜A Huge Disappointmentâ€™", "link": "https://variety.com/2025/film/news/melora-hardin-fired-back-to-the-future-michael-j-fox-1236614891/", "summary": "Melora Hardin, the actor best known for playing Jan Levinson on NBC&#8217;s &#8220;The Office,&#8221; recently told Entertainment Weekly that she &#8220;burst into tears&#8221; when she was fired from Robert Zemeckis&#8217; blockbuster &#8220;Back to the Future.&#8221; While original Marty McFly actor Eric Stoltz being let go from the production and replaced by Michael J. Fox is [&#8230;]", "content": "Melora Hardin, the actor best known for playing Jan Levinson on NBCâ€™s â€œThe Office,â€ recently told Entertainment Weekly that she â€œburst into tearsâ€ when she was fired from Robert Zemeckisâ€™ blockbuster â€œBack to the Future.â€ While original Marty McFly actor Eric Stoltz being let go from the production and replaced by Michael J. Fox is one of Hollywoodâ€™s most infamous re-castings, it turns out that decision led to a second firing. Hardin was originally cast as Martyâ€™s girlfriend Jennifer Parker.\n\nâ€œâ€˜Back to the Futureâ€™ was a huge disappointment. I was 17, you know. I burst into tears,â€ Hardin told EW. â€œIt was very sad. There were quite a few of those that I remember, you know, things that never really got made. But that I remember being very tough.â€\n\nPopular on Variety\n\nHardin revealed earlier this year that she also got the boot from â€œBack to the Futureâ€ when Stoltz was fired because studio executives thought she was too tall to star opposite Michael J. Fox. She explained: â€œIt was apparently the two female executives at the time that thought that it was emasculating for their lead male character to be in scenes with a woman that was taller than him. If I had done it, Iâ€™m sure it would have all gone in a different way. I wouldnâ€™t have done â€˜The Office.'â€\n\nâ€œTo be where I am, you have to have failed more than youâ€™ve succeeded,â€ Hardin now told EW. â€œI think people donâ€™t realize that when they look at it from the outside â€” you have to really be somebody whoâ€™s comfortable with failure, and with putting yourself on the line all the time. That failure doesnâ€™t mean anything about you. You just have to fail better, and keep failing better â€¦ to be able to really weather this career choice.â€\n\nStoltz and Hardin were in production for six weeks on â€œBack to the Futureâ€ when the decision was made to boot Stoltz and recast the lead role with the directorâ€™s first choice, Fox, who had originally been blocked from the film due to his commitment to the NBC sitcom â€œFamily Ties.â€ Hardin was replaced by Claudia Wells. Fox revealed in his new memoir, â€œFuture Boy,â€ that he wrote a letter to Stoltz asking to finally meet 40 years after the recasting.\n\nâ€œEric has maintained his silence on the subject for 40 years, so I was prepared for the likelihood that heâ€™d prefer to keep it that way,â€ Fox writes in the memoir, noting the two had never come face to face to discuss the casting swap. Fox wrote to him: â€œIf your answer is â€˜piss off and leave me aloneâ€™â€¦ That works, too.â€\n\nStoltz responded with a â€œbeautifully written replyâ€ that â€œbegan, â€˜Piss off and leave me alone!â€™ Thankfully, this was followed by â€˜I jestâ€¦â€™ Eric was thoughtful about my outreach, and although he respectfully declined to participate in the book, he seemed open to the idea of getting together.â€\n\nWhen Fox and Stoltz finally found themselves together in the same room, the actors â€œimmediately fell into an easy dialogue about our careers, families, and yes, our own trips through the space-time continuum,â€ Fox writes. â€œ[Stoltz entered] with a smile, and we quickly acknowledged that neither of us had an issue with the other. What transpired on â€˜Back to the Futureâ€™ had not made us enemies or fated rivals; we were just two dedicated actors who had poured equal amounts of energy into the same role. The rest had nothing to do with us. As it turned out, we had much more in common than our spin as Marty.â€", "language": "en", "category": "entertainment", "source": "https://variety.com/feed/", "published": "Tue, 23 Dec 2025 16:06:51 +0000", "fetched_at": "2025-12-23T16:35:19.981063"}
{"title": "Paco LeÃ³nâ€™s â€˜Aida, the Movieâ€™ Landing in the U.S., Puerto Rico, Dominican Republic and Central America", "link": "https://variety.com/2025/film/global/paco-leon-aida-the-movie-wiesner-distribution-outsider-1236615842/", "summary": "â€œAida, the Movie,â€ the feature film spinoff of the wildly successful Spanish TV series â€œAida,â€ is crossing the Atlantic next year, a rare move for a broad Spanish comedy. Wiesner Distribution, marking 25 years as a leading distributor of Ibero-American cinema, will be releasing the ensemble comedy on Feb. 6 across the U.S., Puerto Rico, [&#8230;]", "content": "â€œAida, the Movie,â€ the feature film spinoff of the wildly successful Spanish TV series â€œAida,â€ is crossing the Atlantic next year, a rare move for a broad Spanish comedy.\n\nWiesner Distribution, marking 25 years as a leading distributor of Ibero-American cinema, will be releasing the ensemble comedy on Feb. 6 across the U.S., Puerto Rico, the Dominican Republic and Central Americaâ€™s Costa Rica, Guatemala, El Salvador and Panama. Paul Hudsonâ€™s Outsider Pictures partners with Wiesner on the U.S. release.\n\nThis follows its Spanish theatrical release on Jan. 30 by Sony Pictures Entertainment Iberia.\n\nPopular on Variety\n\nDirected by Spainâ€™s Paco LeÃ³n, whose storied career in film and television kicked off with such comedic gems as â€œCarmina or Blow Up,â€ â€œKiki, Love to Loveâ€ and the â€œAidaâ€ series, the comedy reunites LeÃ³n with his original co-stars from the sitcom, including Carmen Machi, Miren Ibarguren, Mariano PeÃ±a, Eduardo Casanova, Pepe Viyuela, Melani Olivares, Canco RodrÃ­guez, Secun de la Rosa, David Castillo, Marisol Ayuso, Pepa Rus, Ã“scar Reyes and AdriÃ¡n Gordillo. They are joined by 96 other actors, mostly chosen via an open casting call on the filmâ€™s Instagram account.\n\nâ€œAida, the Movieâ€ expands on the story of AÃ­da, a divorcÃ©e struggling to make ends meet while raising her teenage children in the fictional Madrid neighborhood of Esperanza Sur. The massive ensemble series ran from 2005 to 2014 on Spanish broadcast network Telecinco where it became a cult classic and helped launch the international careers of its lead actors.\n\nThe movie is described as a â€œblend of fiction with meta-cinematic storytelling.â€ It takes place during the production of an episode of the series, wryfully blurring the boundaries between actors and characters, both on and off screen, while exploring themes like the limits of humor, the power of comedians and the complexities of fame.\n\nOutsider Pictures and Wiesner Distribution have often teamed up on U.S. theatrical releases, most recently on Gerardo Herreroâ€™s dramedy â€œUnder Therapy.â€ Their upcoming releases include the â€œThe Condorâ€™s Daughter,â€ which premiered at TIFF and was closed at this monthâ€™s Ventana Sur.\n\nâ€œâ€™Aidaâ€™ is a beloved cultural phenomenon that became a massive television hit in Spain. Weâ€™re excited to bring â€˜Aida, the Movieâ€™ to U.S. audiences and share a story whose humor connects effortlessly across cultures, grounded in heart and authenticity,â€ said Cynthia Wiesner, founder and president of Wiesner Distribution.\n\nThe pic is produced by Globomedia, part of The Mediapro Studio, and Telecinco Cinema, with the participation of Mediaset EspaÃ±a and MediterrÃ¡neo Mediaset EspaÃ±a Group.\n\nLeÃ³n, whose international credits include â€œThe Unbearable Weight of Massive Talentâ€ starring Nicolas Cage and Pedro Pascal, and Machi, whose credits include breakout hit â€œFuriousâ€ and Pedro AlmodÃ³varâ€™s â€œIâ€™m So Excited,â€ will be attending the comedyâ€™s Miami premiere on Feb. 5 next year.", "language": "en", "category": "entertainment", "source": "https://variety.com/feed/", "published": "Tue, 23 Dec 2025 16:03:24 +0000", "fetched_at": "2025-12-23T16:35:20.284906"}
{"title": "Playwrights Horizons Sued Over Discount Tickets For BIPOC Audiences", "link": "https://deadline.com/2025/12/playwrights-horizons-lawsuit-1236655764/", "summary": "Playwrights Horizons, one of New York&#8217;s premiere Off Broadway theaters and producers, is being sued by a New Jersey musician who claims that the venue&#8217;s recent discount offered to people of color is racially discriminatory. The lawsuit, filed yesterday in the U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York, alleges that Playwrights Horizons [&#8230;]", "content": "Playwrights Horizons, one of New Yorkâ€™s premiere Off Broadway theaters and producers, is being sued by a New Jersey musician who claims that the venueâ€™s recent discount offered to people of color is racially discriminatory.\n\nThe lawsuit, filed yesterday in the U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York, alleges that Playwrights Horizons violated federal law when it offered discount tickets for a November 6 â€œBIPOC nightâ€ performance of the play Practice. Tickets, according to the suit, â€œwere massively discounted for patrons who identified as black, indigenous, or people of color. For everyone elseâ€”essentially, whitesâ€”tickets were full price.â€\n\nâ€œCharging people different prices based on race is illegal,â€ the suit states, alleging that â€œrace-based pricingâ€ violates federal, state and city law.\n\nWatch on Deadline\n\nThe lawsuit was facilitated by Edward Blum, who, according to The New York Times, is a nationally known lawyer who leads the American Alliance for Equal Rights, an organization that has filed 21 lawsuits in the last two years challenging affirmative action and other race-based policies.\n\nThe plaintiff listed in the suit, Kevin Lynch, is a New Jersey composer, producer and music director. Lynch attended Practice on November 6. The lawsuit says that â€œbecause [Lynch] is white, he paid full price. Many other patrons also paid full price for Practice. All are harmed by Playwrightsâ€™ discriminatory pricing, and all are entitled to recover.â€\n\nThe suit seeks class certification on behalf of all ticket buyers who allegedly paid more for tickets than the discounted amount. According to the suit, Lynch bought two tickets to Practice for $90 each. Patrons using the BIPOC night discount code paid $39 a ticket.\n\nThe class-action complaint, filed by the conservative Arlington, Va., law firm Consovoy McCarthy, seeks unspecified punitive and compensatory damages.\n\nIn a statement to the New York Times, Playwrights Horizons said, â€œThis is a meritless lawsuit, and Playwrights Horizons intends to defend itself in court.â€\n\nThe recent practice of inviting people of color to attend specific performances is an attempt by theater companies to diversify their audiences. The highest-profile example was a 2019 â€œBlack Outâ€ performance of the Broadway production Slave Play; a similar promotion was undertaken for London performances of the play last year, drawing controversy.\n\nPractice, written by Nazareth Hassan and directed by Keenan Tyler Oliphant, began performances October 30 and ran through December 19. The comedic play focuses on a company of actors cast in an avant-garde performance piece.", "language": "en", "category": "entertainment", "source": "https://deadline.com/feed/", "published": "Tue, 23 Dec 2025 16:16:46 +0000", "fetched_at": "2025-12-23T16:35:20.600778"}
{"title": "â€˜Anacondaâ€™ Review: Paul Rudd And Jack Black Hilarious In Inspired Comic Reinvention About 2 Guys Remaking Sonyâ€™s 1997 Giant Snake Movie", "link": "https://deadline.com/2025/12/anaconda-review-paul-rudd-jack-black-comedy-reinvention-1236655668/", "summary": "It is probably too much hypebole to call Sony&#8217;s Anaconda the funniest movie of the year but for my money it really is. It initially started out to be the studio&#8217;s desire to remake or &#8220;reimagine&#8221; their 1997 horror movie of the same name that starred Ice Cube, Jon Voight, and Jennifer Lopez among others [&#8230;]", "content": "It is probably too much hypebole to call Sonyâ€™s Anaconda the funniest movie of the year but for my money it really is. It initially started out to be the studioâ€™s desire to remake or â€œreimagineâ€ their 1997 horror movie of the same name that starred Ice Cube, Jon Voight, and Jennifer Lopez among others and dealt with a National Geographic film crew hijacked by an insane hunter in his quest to bag an elusive giant snake. Studios naturally love to find a way to just repeat their successful IP and Anaconda was enough of a hit to think about a reboot all these years later. If Jumanji keeps working for Sony, why canâ€™t this one also? And director Tom Gormican and his co-screenwriter Kevin Etten had a unique idea, quite an inspired one. Previously they had paired on the very funny 2022 comedy, The Unbearable Weight Of Massive Talent with Nicolas Cage playing a whacked out version of Nicolas Cage.\n\nSimilarly their pitch for this one was to turn it into a comedy vehicle, that also takes satirical shots at the movie business. Two down-on-their-luck guys come to a point in life where they team up to do a remake of their favorite movie as teenagers, Anaconda. Take a sharp premise for laughs and add in the first-ever teaming of Paul Rudd and Jack Black, and you have a recipe for a LOL good time at the movies. Comedy has been in short supply of late, and this one is sort of sneaking in at the end of a year where a traditional movie comedy is suddenly an endangered species. Naked Gun ably filled the bill over the summer, and I loved Aziz Ansariâ€™s Good Forturne with Seth Rogen and Keanu Reeves also in the cast, but that one sadly opened and closed this Fall without making much of an impression on audiences. There just arenâ€™t that many comedies that arenâ€™t also masquerading as something else. This one just wants to make you laugh. It does.\n\nWatch on Deadline\n\nHere Gormican switches up the expected casting by making Black largely the straight man to Ruddâ€™s crazier friend. Doug McCallister (Black) is a frustrated filmmaker stuck in a dead-end job as a wedding videographer, always wanting to sell his blockbuster tentpole ideas to the bride and groom who just only want the traditional treatment, not the blood and gore he has in mind. Ronald Griffin Jr, aka Griff (Rudd) is a failed actor with a few small credits, most notably a 4 episode arc on Swat, who gets fired from his latest job and then comes up with the idea to call Griff, get their school cameraman Kenny (Steve Zahn) and Griffâ€™s ex-girlfriend Claire (Thandiwe Newton) back together to go to the Amazon and do a low budget remake of Anaconda, which through happenstance somehow Doug claims he has the remake rights.\n\nWith a reluctant Doug finally aboard after his wife Malie (Ione Skye) convinces him to live the dream, they all leave Buffalo for the snake infested waters of Brazilâ€™s Amazon. After getting a boat and a captain, Ana (Daniela Melchior) the first order of duty is sign on a title star, and they get one, a professional huge anaconda named Heitor who comes with his trainer and best friend, a local named Santiago (Selton Mello). Though Heitor is claimed to be no more harmful than a puppy, there are some moments of fright for Griff who is a little uneasy acting opposite him and at one point panics and tosses him overboard resulting in Heitorâ€™s gruesome demise. Santiago is distraught and wracked with grief while Doug and Griff now have to figure out how to replace their star with another snake to keep this production afloat. Well isnâ€™t the Amazon full of these things? They will find one. Not a good idea when suddenly the real thing starts to eat everyone for dinner.\n\nWith Australiaâ€™s Queensland coast standing in the Amazon, Gormican skillfully milks all the inherent humor in the situation while also not letting the horror aspects of the original film overtake this one, at least not enough to threaten a PG13 rating. Thankfully he has this cast and a teaming of Rudd and Black who never go into Abbott & Costello territory with the premise but create likeable characters trying to find the spark of life and creative worth they once had in school. And although Black is largely playing it pretty straight he does have a killer signature scene involving a Wild Boar carcass attached to his back as bait for the real anaconda. Priceless Jack Black stuff. The rest of cast fits in nicely , particularly the ever-reliable Zahn and the great Brazilian actor, Mello (Iâ€™m Still Here) who is an amusing scene stealer as the grief stricken anaconda trainer. Without spoiling anything you can also bet on a couple of ace cameos from the original 1997 film.\n\nAs for all the creature action, the VFX work here is first rate as are all the big ass snakes employed to play the real deal.\n\nProducers are Brad Fuller, Andrew Form, Gormican, and Etten.\n\nTitle: Anaconda\n\nDistributor: Sony Pictures\n\nRelease Date: December 25, 2025\n\nDirector: Tom Gormican\n\nScreenplay: Tom Gormican and Kevin Etten\n\nCast: Paul Rudd, Jack Black, Steve Zahn, Thandiwe Newton, Daniel Melchior, Selton Mello, Ione Skye.\n\nRating: PG13\n\nRunning Time: 1 hour and 39 minutes", "language": "en", "category": "entertainment", "source": "https://deadline.com/feed/", "published": "Tue, 23 Dec 2025 16:59:00 +0000", "fetched_at": "2025-12-23T17:00:26.831742"}
{"title": "Russell Brand Charged With Two More Counts Of Rape & Sexual Assault", "link": "https://deadline.com/2025/12/russell-brand-charged-two-more-rape-sexual-assault-1236655804/", "summary": "Russell Brand has been charged with two more counts of rape and sexual assault. The Metropolitan Police said in a statement that the Forgetting Sarah Marshall star&#8217;s charges relate to two further women on top of the previous charges, which were two of rape, one of indecent assault and two of sexual assault. He will [&#8230;]", "content": "Russell Brand has been charged with two more counts of rape and sexual assault.\n\nThe Metropolitan Police said in a statement that the Forgetting Sarah Marshall starâ€™s charges relate to two further women on top of the previous charges, which were two of rape, one of indecent assault and two of sexual assault.\n\nHe will appear in court on January 20 next year in relation to the charges. Six months later, his trial starts for the other charges, for which he has pled not guilty. He has previously denied all charges against him and said he is â€œincredibly gratefulâ€ to be able to defend the charges in court.\n\nâ€œThe women who have made reports, including those connected to the two new charges, continue to receive support from specially trained officers,â€ said the UKâ€™s Metropolitan Police. â€œThe Metâ€™s investigation remains ongoing, and detectives urge anyone affected by this case, or anyone with information, to come forward and speak with police.â€", "language": "en", "category": "entertainment", "source": "https://deadline.com/feed/", "published": "Tue, 23 Dec 2025 16:55:26 +0000", "fetched_at": "2025-12-23T17:00:27.047655"}
{"title": "â€˜Avengers: Doomsdayâ€™ Teaser Unveiled: Chris Evans Is Coming Back As Steve Rogers", "link": "https://deadline.com/2025/12/avengers-doomsday-trailer-steve-rogers-returns-1236655793/", "summary": "Yes, Virigina, there will be Chris Evans as Steve Rogers in Marvel Studios&#8217; Avengers: Doomsday. The Disney studio label and the Russo brothers delivered an early Christmas gift to fans that Captain America is returning, but he&#8217;s a father now with a little baby. The question is whether or not he puts on the suit [&#8230;]", "content": "Yes, Virigina, there will be Chris Evans as Steve Rogers in Marvel Studiosâ€™ Avengers: Doomsday. The Disney studio label and the Russo brothers delivered an early Christmas gift to fans that Captain America is returning, but heâ€™s a father now with a little baby. The question is whether or not he puts on the suit and picks up the shield. The one minute and 20 second teaser shows Rogers picking up his tights and putting them in a box.\n\nWe told you a year ago that Evans was coming back, this despite Evansâ€™ remarks to the press that he wasnâ€™t during The Materialists promo tour.\n\nâ€œI mean, itâ€™s sad to be away. Itâ€™s sad to not be back with the band,â€ Evans told ScreenRant this past summer.\n\nWatch on Deadline\n\nEvans began playing Captain America/Steve Rogers in the 2011 movie Captain America: The First Avenger. He continued to reprise the Captain America role across the MCU until 2019â€™s Avengers: Endgame. The characters passed on the Captain America shield to Anthony Mackieâ€™s Sam Wilson in the Disney+/Marvel series Falcon and the Winter Soldier and Captain America: Brave New World. Evans wound up his role as Rogers in Endgame as an elderly man.\n\nThese bits and bobs of Doomsday teasers are playing in cinemas attached to prints of Avatar: Fire and Ash. Thereâ€™s reportedly a Thor-themed teaser with Chris Hemsworth.\n\nThe Russo brothers last Avengers title, Endgame, is the second highest grossing movie of all-time with $2.799 billion.\n\nAvengers: Doomsday will be the big Christmas movie next year on Dec. 18, 2026.", "language": "en", "category": "entertainment", "source": "https://deadline.com/feed/", "published": "Tue, 23 Dec 2025 16:49:06 +0000", "fetched_at": "2025-12-23T17:00:27.944039"}
{"title": "Taylor Swift Donates $1 Million to Nonprofit Feeding America", "link": "https://variety.com/2025/music/news/taylor-swift-donates-1-million-to-feeding-america-1236616635/", "summary": "Taylor Swift is ringing in the holiday cheer with a sizable donation of $1 million to Feeding America, a nonprofit network of 200 food banks combating hunger in the United States. The charity announced the donation on Instagram, thanking the singer for her act of altruism. &#8220;We are incredibly grateful for Taylor Swift&#8217;s $1 million [&#8230;]", "content": "Taylor Swift is ringing in the holiday cheer with a sizable donation of $1 million to Feeding America, a nonprofit network of 200 food banks combating hunger in the United States.\n\nThe charity announced the donation on Instagram, thanking the singer for her act of altruism. â€œWe are incredibly grateful for Taylor Swiftâ€˜s $1 million gift to Feeding America,â€ reads the post, authored by Feeding America CEO Claire Babineaux-Fontenot. â€œThis holiday season, her continued support is a powerful reminder of whatâ€™s possible when we unite to end hunger. When we join together alongside people facing hunger, we can make sure families have a full table this holiday season and beyond.â€\n\nSwift previously donated $5 million to Feeding America in October 2024 in an effort to provide relief to communities struggling in the wake of Hurricanes Helene and Milton. She also made similar contributions in the past, including $1 million towards natural disaster relief after storms impacted Tennessee in December 2023, as well as $100,000 to the family of a 44-year-old woman killed at the Kansas City Chiefs Super Bowl parade in February 2024.\n\nPopular on Variety\n\nMore recently, Swifties banded together to rally support for Feeding America to help support food banks and those affected by potential cuts in the Supplemental Nutritional Assistance Program (SNAP). Swifties for Hope used social media this past October to encourage fans to donate $13 or whatever they could provide.\n\nSwift is gearing up to release the final two episodes of her docuseries â€œThe End of an Era,â€ which will bow on the service tonight at midnight PT.", "language": "en", "category": "entertainment", "source": "https://variety.com/feed/", "published": "Tue, 23 Dec 2025 17:30:53 +0000", "fetched_at": "2025-12-23T17:32:07.659822"}
{"title": "The Worst TV Shows of 2025", "link": "https://variety.com/lists/worst-tv-shows-of-2025/", "summary": "We are allegedly beyond the namesake apex of peak TV, yet the television landscape remains far too vast for anyone to watch it all; thereâ€™s only so many hours in a day, let alone free ones. With so many new shows to navigate, thereâ€™s no bigger let-down than turning on a series you were excited [&#8230;]", "content": "We are allegedly beyond the namesake apex of peak TV, yet the television landscape remains far too vast for anyone to watch it all; thereâ€™s only so many hours in a day, let alone free ones. With so many new shows to navigate, thereâ€™s no bigger let-down than turning on a series you were excited to indulge in, only for the experience to fall short. As TV critics, itâ€™s our job to tell audiences about the elevated storytelling, worthwhile characters, and transportive settings of the medium at its very best. (You can find our selections for the best shows of 2025 right this way! Thereâ€™s plenty to feel good about.) Regrettably, the flip side of that pursuit means sharing the series that didnâ€™t quite capture our attention or imagination, to spare our readers the same disappointment.\n\nOur list of the yearâ€™s worst TV shows includes spinoffs and stale IP, reminding us all why Hollywood desperately needs to open its doors to new creators and new ideas. There are also promising premises that failed to capitalize on their name-brand stars and intriguing concepts. As the year ends, Variety TV critics Alison Herman and Aramide Tinubu have identified eight series that we definitely wouldnâ€™t recommend to viewers in pursuit of a good time. Of course, everyone has their own unique tastes, so your own mileage may vary â€” though several of our picks have already been canceled, suggesting we werenâ€™t alone in our assessment. From lackluster procedurals to misguided attempts at prestige, read on to see Varietyâ€™s picks for the least successful shows of the year (in alphabetical order).", "language": "en", "category": "entertainment", "source": "https://variety.com/feed/", "published": "Tue, 23 Dec 2025 17:30:00 +0000", "fetched_at": "2025-12-23T17:32:07.889716"}
{"title": "â€˜Legend of Aang: The Last Airbenderâ€™ Skipping Movie Theaters for Paramount+ Streaming Debut", "link": "https://variety.com/2025/film/box-office/legend-of-aang-last-airbender-skipping-theaters-paramount-debut-1236616631/", "summary": "&#8220;Legend of Aang: The Last Airbender&#8221; won&#8217;t play in movie theaters as intended and will instead debut directly on the Paramount+ streaming service. The animated adventure, based on the popular TV series, was slated for release on Oct. 9. &#8220;The Last Airbender&#8221; will now land on the streamer on a yet-to-be-determined date in the fall. [&#8230;]", "content": "â€œLegend of Aang: The Last Airbenderâ€ wonâ€™t play in movie theaters as intended and will instead debut directly on the Paramount+ streaming service.\n\nThe animated adventure, based on the popular TV series, was slated for release on Oct. 9. â€œThe Last Airbenderâ€ will now land on the streamer on a yet-to-be-determined date in the fall.\n\nMore to comeâ€¦", "language": "en", "category": "entertainment", "source": "https://variety.com/feed/", "published": "Tue, 23 Dec 2025 17:24:33 +0000", "fetched_at": "2025-12-23T17:32:08.096288"}
{"title": "Mads Mikkelsen on â€˜Freezing to Deathâ€™ Filming â€˜Rogue Oneâ€™ and How the Script Was â€˜Surprisingly Unfinishedâ€™: â€˜I Donâ€™t Think They Ever Locked a Draftâ€™", "link": "https://variety.com/2025/film/news/mads-mikkelsen-star-wars-rogue-one-script-1236615584/", "summary": "While looking back on his career with Variety, Mads Mikkelsen recounted his experience working on the 2016 â€œStar Warsâ€ prequel â€œRogue One,â€ saying that the script was &#8220;surprisingly unfinished&#8221; while filming.Â Â  â€œIt kept changing,â€ he explained. â€œOne would think that that was already done. I don&#8217;t think they ever locked a draft. I think they [&#8230;]", "content": "While looking back on his career with Variety, Mads Mikkelsen recounted his experience working on the 2016 â€œStar Warsâ€ prequel â€œRogue One,â€ saying that the script was â€œsurprisingly unfinishedâ€ while filming.\n\nâ€œIt kept changing,â€ he explained. â€œOne would think that that was already done. I donâ€™t think they ever locked a draft. I think they kept working on it and improvised and went back and reshot stuff and then came up with a better idea, which is kind of livable for a character like mine. I mean, I had my mission. I knew what it was, but it was obviously tricky for the two young heroes, not knowing exactly what they were carrying into a room of baggage.â€\n\nMikkelsen played Galen Erso in the film. He starred alongside actors including Felicity Jones as Jyn Erso, Diego Luna as Cassian Andor, Ben Mendelsohn as Orson Krennic and Donnie Yen as Chirrut Ãmwe. Directed by Gareth Edwards, the â€œStar Warsâ€ anthology film follows a band of resistance fighters as they embark on a mission to steal the plans for the Death Star.\n\nPopular on Variety\n\nHe also noted that the scene where he says, â€œIt must be destroyedâ€ while water rains down on him was particularly difficult to re-shoot as the story kept changing.\n\nâ€œThat was a brutal, I would say day, but it was days, because there was a lot of changes in the story,â€ the actor said. â€œWe went back and forth, and it was raining. When you do artificial rain, it is almost impossible to do that in a long scene without having ice cold water. So I was lying there, freezing to death, trying to keep my eyes open.â€\n\nMikkelsen also revisited his other acclaimed roles including â€œCasino Royaleâ€ for Variety, sharing that he and co-star Daniel Craig were asked to stop improvising during filming, and that Craig was the only cast member who didnâ€™t know how to play poker.\n\nâ€œHe was the only guy in that film who did not know how to play poker, and he ran away with $150 million of my dollars,â€ said Mikkelsen.\n\nMost recently, Mikkelsen starred in Bryan Fullerâ€™s feature film debut â€œDust Bunny,â€ which premiered on Dec. 12.\n\nWatch the full video here:", "language": "en", "category": "entertainment", "source": "https://variety.com/feed/", "published": "Tue, 23 Dec 2025 17:20:00 +0000", "fetched_at": "2025-12-23T17:32:08.310768"}
{"title": "Russell Brand Charged With More Counts of Rape and Sexual Assault", "link": "https://variety.com/2025/tv/global/russell-brand-charged-further-counts-rape-sexual-assault-1236616617/", "summary": "Russell Brand has been charged with further offences. London&#8217;s Metropolitan Police said Tuesday that the disgraced comedian, actor and TV host had been issued with two additional charges: one count of rape and one count of sexual assault. The allegations relate to two further women on top of the previous charges against the &#8220;Forgetting Sarah [&#8230;]", "content": "Russell Brand has been charged with further offences.\n\nLondonâ€™s Metropolitan Police said Tuesday that the disgraced comedian, actor and TV host had been issued with two additional charges: one count of rape and one count of sexual assault.\n\nThe allegations relate to two further women on top of the previous charges against the â€œForgetting Sarah Marshallâ€ star, which included two of rape, one of indecent assault and two of sexual assault.\n\nBrand will now appear at Westminster Magistratesâ€™ Court on Jan. 20 in relation to the additional charges.\n\nPopular on Variety\n\nEarlier this year, Brand appeared in Londonâ€™s Southwark Crown Court and pleaded not guilty to the previous charges. The allegations, involving four women, relate to incidents that occurred between 1999 and 2005. The trial for these charges is due to start on June 3, 2026. He will remain on conditional bail until then.\n\nâ€œThe women who have made reports, including those connected to the two new charges, continue to receive support from specially trained officers,â€ said the Met Policeâ€™s detective chief inspector Tariq Farooqi in relation to the new allegations. Farooqi added that the Metâ€™s investigation, first launched after the police received several allegations in the wake of a major expose in 2023 from both Channel 4â€™s â€œDispatchesâ€ documentary series and The Sunday Times, â€œremains ongoing,â€ and urged anyone affected by the case or with information to come forward.\n\nThe 2023 expose saw Brand accused of â€œrape, sexual assaults and emotional abuse.â€ A rep for the show said that â€œFive women, four of whom asked to remain anonymous, agreed to share their stories of serious sexual allegations in the program.â€\n\nJust months after the expose ran, Brand converted to Christianity and has been outspoken about his new faith. Last year he prayed on stage with Tucker Carlson and later Jordan Petersen at events in the U.S.", "language": "en", "category": "entertainment", "source": "https://variety.com/feed/", "published": "Tue, 23 Dec 2025 17:04:26 +0000", "fetched_at": "2025-12-23T17:32:08.581980"}
{"title": "Connor Storrie Thought â€˜Heated Rivalryâ€™ Book Fans Would â€˜Hate My Performanceâ€™ and Heâ€™d Get â€˜Torn Apartâ€™ Before Show Became a Hit", "link": "https://variety.com/2025/tv/news/connor-storrie-heated-rivalry-fans-performance-1236616636/", "summary": "Before â€œHeated Rivalryâ€ quickly became a global television phenomenon, star Connor Storrie wasnâ€™t quite sure how fans would receive his portrayal of the Russian hockey player Ilya Rozanov â€” especially having seen â€œadaptations be torn apart online previously,â€ he said on a recent podcast episode of â€œShut Up Evanâ€ hosted by Evan Ross Katz.Â  â€œI&#8217;m [&#8230;]", "content": "Before â€œHeated Rivalryâ€ quickly became a global television phenomenon, star Connor Storrie wasnâ€™t quite sure how fans would receive his portrayal of the Russian hockey player Ilya Rozanov â€” especially having seen â€œadaptations be torn apart online previously,â€ he said on a recent podcast episode of â€œShut Up Evanâ€ hosted by Evan Ross Katz.\n\nâ€œIâ€™m very optimistic, but Iâ€™m also a firm believer in optimistic nihilism: accept the worst, but expect the best,â€ Storrie continued. â€œI went through this entire process, even if it sounds pessimistic, accepting the worst case, which is that theyâ€™re going to hate my performance, Iâ€™m so wrong for the part [and] itâ€™s going to be torn apart by people who love the book, and be like, well, if that were the case, all I can do is really try to give an honest performance and trust that Jacob [Tierney] knows the story well enough to to bring the right moments to it.â€\n\nPopular on Variety\n\nThe show, which centers on a decade-long secret relationship between Rozanov and fellow hockey player Shane Hollander (Hudson Williams), was created by Jacob Tierney, who adapted the material from author Rachel Reidâ€™s popular â€œGame Changersâ€ book series. Since the showâ€™s debut in November, it has swiftly topped the charts: the Crave-created romance has become the Canadian streamerâ€™s most-watched original series and HBO Maxâ€™s top-rated non-animated acquired series.\n\nThe center of conversation has been Williamâ€™s and Storrieâ€™s performances. Later in the podcast, Storrie discussed how he approaches significant moments in the show that book fans will have expectations for.\n\nâ€œFor moments like that,â€ Storrie explained, referring to his now-viral â€œIâ€™m coming to the cottageâ€ moment at the end of the fifth episode, â€œI had some ideas about trying to really play to the book. But Jacob just knows that book. He knows that story like the back of his hand. I read the book twice, read all the scripts a million times.â€\n\nStorrie also noted the importance of not getting too wrapped up in â€œtrying to please the fans.â€ â€œHonestly, I think with acting or art in general, trying to feed too much into what you think other people want is kind of the death of anything thatâ€™s actually humane and inspiring.â€", "language": "en", "category": "entertainment", "source": "https://variety.com/feed/", "published": "Tue, 23 Dec 2025 17:52:32 +0000", "fetched_at": "2025-12-23T17:53:58.176513"}
{"title": "â€˜The Legend Of Aang: The Last Airbenderâ€™ Wonâ€™t Play Theaters, Will Debut On Paramount+ Instead", "link": "https://deadline.com/2025/12/the-legend-of-aang-the-last-airbender-paramount-skip-theaters-1236655848/", "summary": "The Legend of Aang: The Last Airbender, which was greenlit by the previous Paramount Animation administration, won&#8217;t be getting a theatrical release, rather it&#8217;s headed to Paramount+ next fall. The movie&#8217;s most recent release date was Oct. 9, 2026. It had jumped around the calendar, first set of Oct. 10, 2025, then Jan. 30, 2026. [&#8230;]", "content": "The Legend of Aang: The Last Airbender, which was greenlit by the previous Paramount Animation administration, wonâ€™t be getting a theatrical release, rather itâ€™s headed to Paramount+ next fall.\n\nThe movieâ€™s most recent release date was Oct. 9, 2026. It had jumped around the calendar, first set of Oct. 10, 2025, then Jan. 30, 2026. In Comscore that leaves nine theatrical releases date for Paramount, the first up being the Jan. 9 Walter Hamada produced genre movie Primate. Paramount announced last month that next year will count at least 15 theatrical releases.\n\nIn the movie, directed by Lauren Montgomery with Steve Ahn and William Mata, Avatar Aang, the worldâ€™s last Airbender, learns of an ancient power that could save his culture from extinction. With the help of his friends, he embarks on a global quest to find it before it falls into the wrong hands and threatens to upend the peace they sacrificed everything to achieve. Voice cast includes Taika Waititi, Geraldine Viswanathan, Dee Bradley Baker, Freida Pinto and Ke Huy Quan, joining previously announced Dave Bautista, Eric Nam, Jessica Matten, Dionne Quan, RomÃ¡n Zaragoza and Steven Yeun.\n\nWatch on Deadline\n\nThereâ€™s also a new 2D series coming to P+, that being Avatar: Seven Havens from Avatar Studios. That series from Nickelodeon Animation is set in a world shattered by a devastating cataclysm where a young Earthbender discovers sheâ€™s the new Avatar after Korra. But in this dangerous era, that title marks her as humanityâ€™s destroyer, not its savior. Hunted by both human and spirit enemies, she and her long-lost twin must uncover their mysterious origins and save the Seven Havens before civilizationâ€™s last strongholds collapse. The series is comprised of Book 1 (13 half-hour episodes) and Book 2 (13 half-hour episodes). Michael DiMartino and Bryan Konietzko serve as co-creators and executive producers. Ethan Spaulding is executive producer, and Sehaj Sethi is co-executive producer.\n\nBoth properties are based on the original series Avatar: The Last Airbender created by Michael Dante DiMartino and Bryan Konietzko. The new movie and new series join The Legend of Korra and Avatar: The Last Airbender on Paramount+. The original series ranks among Nielsenâ€™s Top 100 most-streamed titles during 17 of 139 weeks since its debut on the OTT service in March 2023.", "language": "en", "category": "entertainment", "source": "https://deadline.com/feed/", "published": "Tue, 23 Dec 2025 17:40:53 +0000", "fetched_at": "2025-12-23T17:53:58.567866"}
